1
00:01:15,900 --> 00:01:17,800
Replacement team's here, sir.

2
00:01:18,000 --> 00:01:19,000
Right.

3
00:01:19,200 --> 00:01:21,200
Come on through.

4
00:01:22,600 --> 00:01:25,300
20 minutes and we were gonna
start looking for you.

5
00:01:25,500 --> 00:01:27,900
Yeah. It's really something out there.

6
00:01:28,200 --> 00:01:30,200
- You look a mess, sir.
- Yeah?

7
00:01:30,300 --> 00:01:32,300
Your turn next, Ginsburg.

8
00:01:39,200 --> 00:01:41,100
OK. I'll see you in 24.

9
00:01:41,300 --> 00:01:43,000
See you tomorrow.

10
00:01:47,700 --> 00:01:49,700
What was that you were you saying?

11
00:01:49,900 --> 00:01:53,400
You used to hear her chant
all night long. Om mahneypod me om.

12
00:01:53,700 --> 00:01:56,100
- Om mahneypod me om.
- Over the plants?

13
00:01:56,300 --> 00:01:59,400
She'd cup her hands over those seeds
and chant by the hour.

14
00:01:59,700 --> 00:02:02,600
She grew the most beautiful
wandoos you ever saw, man.

15
00:02:03,000 --> 00:02:04,900
Primo stuff. Resin city.

16
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:12,000
Stand clear.

17
00:02:20,600 --> 00:02:23,900
The commander's been worried
about you. The roads must be a bear.

18
00:02:24,100 --> 00:02:26,200
- What roads?
- Visibility.

19
00:02:26,500 --> 00:02:31,000
Visibility? Bullshit. You guys haven't
been on time for the last six months.

20
00:02:31,300 --> 00:02:34,800
- I wrote you guys up in the logbook.
- Yeah. You're a prince, Bevan.

21
00:02:36,900 --> 00:02:38,800
Good night, gentlemen!

22
00:02:49,500 --> 00:02:51,700
So, that was like sinsemilia, right?

23
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:55,500
Sinsemilla. This grass made
Thai stick taste like oregano.

24
00:02:55,700 --> 00:02:57,700
Lay you out flat, man.

25
00:03:01,900 --> 00:03:04,000
- Got a red light, sir.
- What on?

26
00:03:04,200 --> 00:03:06,200
Number eight. Warhead alarm.

27
00:03:06,400 --> 00:03:08,500
Give it a thump with your finger.

28
00:03:13,100 --> 00:03:15,200
Alarm reset.

29
00:03:29,500 --> 00:03:33,700
Skybird, this is Dropkick with
a Red dash Alpha message in two parts.

30
00:03:34,100 --> 00:03:36,000
Break. Break. Red dash Alpha.

31
00:03:36,200 --> 00:03:38,700
- Stand by to copy message.
- Standing by.

32
00:03:38,900 --> 00:03:42,100
Romeo OscarNovember Charlie

33
00:03:42,400 --> 00:03:45,800
Tango Tango Lima Alpha.

34
00:03:46,100 --> 00:03:52,100
Authentication: 220040 Delta

35
00:03:52,500 --> 00:03:54,000
Lima.

36
00:03:54,200 --> 00:03:57,100
I have a valid message.
Stand by to authenticate.

37
00:03:57,400 --> 00:03:59,800
I agree with authentication also, sir.

38
00:04:16,600 --> 00:04:19,200
- Enter launch code.
- Entering launch code.

39
00:04:25,200 --> 00:04:28,700
- Launch order confirmed.
- Holy shit!

40
00:04:33,800 --> 00:04:38,000
Target selection: complete.
Time on target sequence: complete.

41
00:04:38,400 --> 00:04:41,600
- Yield selection: complete.
- Begin countdown. Tminus 60.

42
00:04:41,800 --> 00:04:44,800
- All right. Let's do it. Insert launch key.
- Stand by.

43
00:04:45,800 --> 00:04:48,500
- Launch key inserted.
- Roger.

44
00:04:48,800 --> 00:04:51,900
On my mark... rotate launch key to Set.

45
00:04:52,900 --> 00:04:55,500
Three... two... one...

46
00:04:56,500 --> 00:04:58,700
- Mark.
- Tminus 50.

47
00:05:08,900 --> 00:05:10,900
Roger. At Set.

48
00:05:17,100 --> 00:05:18,800
- Sir?
- Tminus 40.

49
00:05:19,000 --> 00:05:22,300
- Enable missiles.
- Number one enabled. Two enabled.

50
00:05:22,600 --> 00:05:25,800
- Three enabled.
- Get somebody on the goddamn phone.

51
00:05:28,800 --> 00:05:30,100
Seven... eight...

52
00:05:32,200 --> 00:05:34,200
Nine...

53
00:05:37,100 --> 00:05:38,600
Ten. All missiles enabled.

54
00:05:38,800 --> 00:05:42,800
- Get me Wing Command Post. Direct line.
- That's not the correct procedure.

55
00:05:43,100 --> 00:05:46,300
- Try SAC Headquarters on the HF.
- That's not the procedure.

56
00:05:46,700 --> 00:05:50,800
I want somebody on the goddamn phone
before I kill 20 million people.

57
00:05:54,800 --> 00:05:56,300
T minus 20.

58
00:05:56,500 --> 00:06:00,300
I got nothin' here! They might
have been knocked out already.

59
00:06:00,500 --> 00:06:02,000
Right.

60
00:06:02,200 --> 00:06:05,300
On my mark,
rotate launch keys to Launch.

61
00:06:05,500 --> 00:06:07,700
Roger. Ready to go to Launch.

62
00:06:07,900 --> 00:06:10,100
- Fourteen...
- Thirteen... twelve...

63
00:06:10,400 --> 00:06:11,600
Eleven...

64
00:06:14,700 --> 00:06:18,100
Seven... six...

65
00:06:18,300 --> 00:06:20,500
- Five...
- Sir, we have a launch order.

66
00:06:20,900 --> 00:06:23,900
- Three... two...
- Put your hand on the key, sir.

67
00:06:24,100 --> 00:06:25,900
One... Launch!

68
00:06:28,700 --> 00:06:33,000
- Sir, we are at launch! Turn your key!
- I'm sorry. I'm so sorry.

69
00:06:33,300 --> 00:06:35,800
Turn your key, sir!

70
00:08:25,300 --> 00:08:27,400
They're cleared. Go ahead and open it up.

71
00:08:31,100 --> 00:08:35,300
- Hello. I'm Pat Healy.
- I'm Lyle Watson. This is Arthur Cabot.

72
00:08:35,700 --> 00:08:40,100
I'm Pat Healy, Dr McKittrick's assistant.
I've got some passes for you here.

73
00:08:40,500 --> 00:08:43,200
We had scheduled a meeting
pending your arrival.

74
00:08:43,400 --> 00:08:46,000
If you have any questions,
feel free to ask me.

75
00:08:46,300 --> 00:08:49,200
I'd be happy to fill you in
if there's any way I can.

76
00:09:44,100 --> 00:09:46,000
They're here.

77
00:09:46,200 --> 00:09:47,700
Good.

78
00:09:47,900 --> 00:09:49,300
Let's go.

79
00:09:51,000 --> 00:09:54,500
Cabot and Watson came alone.
No senators. No congressmen.

80
00:09:54,700 --> 00:09:58,900
I wish they'd brought a few senators.
I'd like to tell 'em what's going on here.

81
00:09:59,300 --> 00:10:01,800
John, please! Don't start that right away.

82
00:10:02,000 --> 00:10:04,500
I had them on the phone
and they're calmed down.

83
00:10:06,600 --> 00:10:11,800
Well, are we positive that these men had
no way of knowing this was only a test?

84
00:10:12,100 --> 00:10:15,600
Lyle, for God's sakes! How many times
are we gonna go through this?

85
00:10:16,100 --> 00:10:19,200
- It doesn't make any difference.
- I've spoken to these men.

86
00:10:19,500 --> 00:10:21,700
They all believed it was the real deal.

87
00:10:21,900 --> 00:10:24,500
Look, we gotta be on a plane
in less than an hour.

88
00:10:24,900 --> 00:10:28,900
I have to explain to the president
why 22% of his missile commanders

89
00:10:29,100 --> 00:10:33,600
failed to launch their missiles. What
am I supposed to say? 22% isn't so bad?

90
00:10:34,000 --> 00:10:38,500
The president knows that I am fully
responsible for the men in my command.

91
00:10:38,800 --> 00:10:42,600
I've ordered a re-evaluation of
our psychological screening procedure.

92
00:10:42,900 --> 00:10:45,200
Wait a minute. Excuse me, General.

93
00:10:45,400 --> 00:10:48,300
We can't ask these men
to go back to the president

94
00:10:48,600 --> 00:10:52,700
with a lot of headshrinker horseshit!
You can't screen out human response!

95
00:10:53,000 --> 00:10:57,600
Those men know what it means to turn
the keys, and some are just not up to it!

96
00:10:57,900 --> 00:11:00,500
Now, it's as simple as that!

97
00:11:04,200 --> 00:11:07,000
I think we oughta take
the men out of the loop.

98
00:11:07,200 --> 00:11:10,600
- Mr McKittrick, you're out of line, sir.
- Why am I out of line?

99
00:11:10,900 --> 00:11:12,300
Excuse me!

100
00:11:13,800 --> 00:11:17,100
I'm sorry. I don't understand.
Take them out of the loop?

101
00:11:17,300 --> 00:11:20,000
Gentlemen! We've had men in these silos

102
00:11:20,200 --> 00:11:23,600
since before any of you
were watching Howdy Doody.

103
00:11:26,200 --> 00:11:30,600
For myself, I sleep pretty well at night
knowing those boys are down there.

104
00:11:31,000 --> 00:11:34,900
General, we know they're fine men,
but in a nuclear war we can't afford

105
00:11:35,200 --> 00:11:37,800
to have missiles
lying dormant in those silos

106
00:11:38,100 --> 00:11:41,800
because those men refuse to turn
the keys when the computers tell 'em to!

107
00:11:42,000 --> 00:11:44,200
You mean when
the president orders them to.

108
00:11:44,400 --> 00:11:48,900
The president will probably follow
the computer war plan. That's a fact!

109
00:11:49,200 --> 00:11:51,900
I imagine the Joint Chiefs
will have some input.

110
00:11:52,100 --> 00:11:54,600
- You're damn tootin'.
- Well, hell...

111
00:11:54,800 --> 00:11:57,200
In a surprise attack, there's no time.

112
00:11:57,600 --> 00:12:00,000
23 minutes from warning to impact.

113
00:12:00,200 --> 00:12:03,200
- Six minutes if it's sub-launched.
- Six minutes.

114
00:12:03,500 --> 00:12:07,100
That's barely enough time
for the president to make a decision.

115
00:12:07,500 --> 00:12:10,300
Once he makes the decision,
the computer should take over.

116
00:12:10,500 --> 00:12:14,100
Now, sir, I know that you've got
a plane waiting for you,

117
00:12:14,300 --> 00:12:17,700
but if you could indulge me,
I'd like to show you something.

118
00:12:25,300 --> 00:12:28,600
These computers give instant access
to the state of the world.

119
00:12:28,800 --> 00:12:32,100
Troop movements, Soviet
missile tests, weather patterns.

120
00:12:32,400 --> 00:12:36,100
It all flows into this room,
and then into the WOPR computer.

121
00:12:36,300 --> 00:12:39,700
- WOPR? What is that?
- War Operation Plan Response.

122
00:12:40,100 --> 00:12:41,800
This is Mr Richter.

123
00:12:42,000 --> 00:12:45,700
Paul, would you like to tell
these gentlemen about the WOPR?

124
00:12:45,900 --> 00:12:50,300
Well, the WOPR spends all its time
thinking about World War Ill.

125
00:12:50,600 --> 00:12:57,500
24 hours a day, 365 days a year,
it plays an endless series of war games

126
00:12:58,000 --> 00:13:01,400
using all available information
on the state of the world.

127
00:13:01,700 --> 00:13:05,400
The WOPR has already fought
World War Ill, as a game,

128
00:13:05,700 --> 00:13:07,600
time and time again.

129
00:13:07,800 --> 00:13:10,900
It estimates Soviet responses
to our responses

130
00:13:11,200 --> 00:13:13,400
to their responses, and so on.

131
00:13:13,700 --> 00:13:16,100
Estimates damage. Counts the dead.

132
00:13:16,400 --> 00:13:19,000
Then it looks for ways
to improve its score...

133
00:13:19,200 --> 00:13:21,600
The point is that the key decisions

134
00:13:21,800 --> 00:13:24,800
of every option have already
been made by the WOPR.

135
00:13:25,000 --> 00:13:28,500
So all this trillion-dollar hardware
is really at the mercy

136
00:13:28,900 --> 00:13:31,100
of those men with the little brass keys?

137
00:13:31,400 --> 00:13:34,900
That's exactly right. Whose only problem
is that they're human beings.

138
00:13:35,300 --> 00:13:39,900
But in 30 days we could put in electronic
relays. Get the men out of the loop.

139
00:13:40,200 --> 00:13:41,700
Gentlemen...

140
00:13:43,000 --> 00:13:47,400
I wouldn't trust this overgrown pile of
microchips further than I could throw it.

141
00:13:47,700 --> 00:13:53,100
I don't know if you wanna trust the safety
of our country to some... silicon diode...

142
00:13:53,500 --> 00:13:56,900
Nobody is talking about entrusting
the safety of the nation

143
00:13:57,300 --> 00:13:59,200
to a machine, for God's sake!

144
00:13:59,300 --> 00:14:02,200
We'll keep control,
but here at the top where it belongs.

145
00:14:02,600 --> 00:14:03,900
All right, gentlemen.

146
00:14:04,000 --> 00:14:08,000
I think I'm going to recommend
McKittrick's idea to the president.

147
00:14:08,300 --> 00:14:10,700
And I'll get back to you on this.

148
00:14:12,700 --> 00:14:14,600
You won't regret this.

149
00:14:36,900 --> 00:14:39,000
OK. You had fries and a Coke, right?

150
00:14:57,700 --> 00:14:59,600
Damn!

151
00:15:02,200 --> 00:15:04,100
- Hi, David!
- Hi, Howie!

152
00:15:05,400 --> 00:15:07,300
- How's it going?
- Pretty good.

153
00:15:10,900 --> 00:15:13,600
- You wanna take this over? I gotta go.
- Sure!

154
00:15:13,900 --> 00:15:15,800
- Go ahead.
- Thanks!

155
00:15:19,600 --> 00:15:21,500
- Bye, David!
- Bye!

156
00:15:31,200 --> 00:15:34,900
All right. Question number two.

157
00:15:35,300 --> 00:15:42,800
Seeds that are germinated in water
before they are planted will... what?

158
00:15:43,200 --> 00:15:45,500
- Robert?
- Sprout roots?

159
00:15:45,700 --> 00:15:47,300
Ah! David!

160
00:15:47,600 --> 00:15:51,800
Nice of you to join us.
Oh, David. I have a little present for you.

161
00:16:02,800 --> 00:16:06,000
Question number four.
In the history of science,

162
00:16:06,200 --> 00:16:09,600
novel and innovative concepts
occasionally arise

163
00:16:10,000 --> 00:16:12,400
from sudden left-field inspiration.

164
00:16:12,600 --> 00:16:14,300
Miss Mack...

165
00:16:14,500 --> 00:16:17,700
Could you tell us your answer
to question number four?

166
00:16:18,000 --> 00:16:21,300
Why do nitrogen nodules
cling to the roots of plants?

167
00:16:24,100 --> 00:16:26,100
Love?

168
00:16:29,300 --> 00:16:33,600
Jennifer, what do you know about
nitrogen nodules that we don't?

169
00:16:33,900 --> 00:16:37,300
Some bit of salacious info
to which you alone are privy?

170
00:16:38,100 --> 00:16:40,000
- No.
- I see.

171
00:16:40,100 --> 00:16:43,300
No, you didn't know
the correct answer - symbiosis.

172
00:16:44,900 --> 00:16:47,800
Because you don't pay attention in class.

173
00:16:51,600 --> 00:16:53,600
- Thank you.
- You're welcome.

174
00:16:53,800 --> 00:16:58,800
There seems to be a lot of confusion on
this next question - asexual reproduction.

175
00:17:00,400 --> 00:17:02,300
Could someone tell me, please

176
00:17:02,600 --> 00:17:07,700
who first suggested the idea
of reproduction without sex?

177
00:17:16,200 --> 00:17:17,700
- Miss Mack!
- Yes?

178
00:17:17,900 --> 00:17:20,400
What is so amusing?

179
00:17:23,600 --> 00:17:24,900
What?

180
00:17:25,100 --> 00:17:27,700
All right, Lightman.

181
00:17:27,900 --> 00:17:32,900
Maybe you can tell us who first suggested
the idea of reproduction without sex.

182
00:17:33,300 --> 00:17:35,500
Your wife?

183
00:17:39,800 --> 00:17:42,000
Get out, Lightman! Get out!

184
00:17:50,400 --> 00:17:54,100
Mr Ligget wants me to discuss
my attitude problem with Mr Kessler.

185
00:17:54,400 --> 00:17:57,600
I think Mr Kessler's getting tired
of your attitude problem.

186
00:17:57,900 --> 00:17:59,400
Me, too.

187
00:18:30,500 --> 00:18:33,600
Lightman. What a... surprise.

188
00:18:33,900 --> 00:18:35,800
Won't you come in?

189
00:18:50,900 --> 00:18:52,800
Hi!

190
00:18:53,100 --> 00:18:54,100
Hi!

191
00:18:54,200 --> 00:18:57,100
Sorry if I got you in trouble.
I couldn't stop laughing.

192
00:18:57,400 --> 00:18:59,400
That's OK. You were perfect.

193
00:18:59,600 --> 00:19:01,600
- I was?
- Yeah.

194
00:19:01,700 --> 00:19:03,600
- You want a ride home?
- Yeah.

195
00:19:05,900 --> 00:19:07,800
Hop on.

196
00:19:15,200 --> 00:19:18,300
- So you got an F on that test today, too?
- Yep.

197
00:19:18,500 --> 00:19:21,200
Guess we're both gonna be
stuck in summer school.

198
00:19:21,500 --> 00:19:24,300
- Not me.
- Why not? You have to make up biology.

199
00:19:25,200 --> 00:19:27,400
- I don't think so.
- Why not?

200
00:19:29,100 --> 00:19:32,100
- Why not? Come on! Tell me. Why not?
- Make a left.

201
00:19:32,300 --> 00:19:35,300
Why don't you come up to my house
and I'll show you?

202
00:19:35,500 --> 00:19:37,500
What are you gonna show me?

203
00:19:37,700 --> 00:19:40,800
I'm gonna show you.
I'll show you how you do it.

204
00:19:42,400 --> 00:19:44,900
- Hi, Bo!
- Oh! Hi, Bo!

205
00:19:45,200 --> 00:19:47,100
Hey, Bo! How you doin'?

206
00:20:04,700 --> 00:20:06,700
My room's upstairs.

207
00:20:06,900 --> 00:20:09,900
- Your parents aren't home?
- No. They both work.

208
00:20:28,300 --> 00:20:30,200
A little mess.

209
00:20:30,400 --> 00:20:32,400
It's OK. You should see my room.

210
00:20:42,000 --> 00:20:44,800
- You're really into computers, huh?
- Yeah.

211
00:20:49,400 --> 00:20:53,500
- What are you doing?
- I'm dialling into the school's computer.

212
00:21:05,800 --> 00:21:10,400
They change the password every couple
of weeks, but I know where they write it.

213
00:21:24,300 --> 00:21:26,200
- Are those your grades?!
- Yeah.

214
00:21:27,200 --> 00:21:29,600
I don't think that I deserved an F, do you?

215
00:21:33,700 --> 00:21:36,200
- You can't do that!
- Already done.

216
00:21:38,900 --> 00:21:41,800
- Do you have a middle initial?
- K. Katherine.

217
00:21:47,500 --> 00:21:49,800
Those are my grades.

218
00:21:50,000 --> 00:21:53,700
- How can anybody get a D in home ec?
- That's none of your business.

219
00:21:54,000 --> 00:21:56,300
- Can you erase this?
- No. It's too late.

220
00:21:56,500 --> 00:21:58,300
What are you doing?

221
00:21:58,500 --> 00:22:02,300
- I'm changing your biology grade.
- No. You'll get me in trouble.

222
00:22:02,600 --> 00:22:06,400
Nobody can find out. You got a C!
Now you won't go to summer school.

223
00:22:06,600 --> 00:22:08,600
- Change it back.
- Why? They can't...

224
00:22:08,900 --> 00:22:11,900
- I said change it back.
- OK. OK.

225
00:22:20,300 --> 00:22:22,100
I guess I'd better get going.

226
00:22:23,700 --> 00:22:25,700
Thanks for the ride.

227
00:22:26,500 --> 00:22:28,600
Yeah. OK. Bye.

228
00:22:28,800 --> 00:22:30,800
Bye.

229
00:23:30,500 --> 00:23:34,500
Get down. Get down. You've already
had your dinner. Now just sit.

230
00:23:34,700 --> 00:23:36,700
Sit! Stay!

231
00:23:37,000 --> 00:23:39,600
- Don't forget to take out the garbage.
- David.

232
00:23:39,900 --> 00:23:42,600
- Put that lid on real tight.
- I know, Ma.

233
00:23:44,500 --> 00:23:47,000
Yes, they will carry back on the second.

234
00:23:48,500 --> 00:23:51,800
Sure. I think we can really work out
some creative financing.

235
00:23:53,800 --> 00:23:55,700
Oh, but you've gotta see it!

236
00:23:56,000 --> 00:23:58,600
There's a Jacuzzi
in the master bedroom...

237
00:24:10,300 --> 00:24:12,400
Oh, sure. We can work that out.

238
00:24:13,500 --> 00:24:17,500
That is true. You'll have a balloon
payment at the end of five years.

239
00:24:17,800 --> 00:24:21,100
But that's nothing.
The economy is gonna be great then.

240
00:24:21,400 --> 00:24:23,300
He who dances must pay the piper.

