- Get me the president on the horn.
- Yes, sir.

484
00:44:37,100 --> 00:44:40,700
Mr President? This is Beringer at NORAD.

485
00:44:41,000 --> 00:44:42,900
Oh, attack!

486
00:44:43,100 --> 00:44:46,700
- I wonder if I should use my subs.
- Sure. Give 'em the works.

487
00:44:47,100 --> 00:44:49,000
David!

488
00:44:50,600 --> 00:44:52,400
Excuse me.

489
00:44:52,600 --> 00:44:54,600
David!

490
00:44:55,300 --> 00:44:58,400
How many times have I told you
to fasten these lids on tight?!

491
00:44:58,800 --> 00:45:01,500
- Look at this mess!
- I'll be down in a few minutes.

492
00:45:01,700 --> 00:45:04,300
Now! Come down now!
I want this cleared up now!

493
00:45:04,600 --> 00:45:08,500
Come down here and do what
your father asks you to pronto, David.

494
00:45:09,400 --> 00:45:11,300
We're gonna barbecue tonight.

495
00:45:11,500 --> 00:45:14,700
- You wanna invite your little friend?
- Please!

496
00:45:14,900 --> 00:45:15,900
David!

497
00:45:18,300 --> 00:45:20,300
Shit!

498
00:45:26,200 --> 00:45:28,100
Little friend.

499
00:45:35,600 --> 00:45:40,300
Mr President, something's happening.
I'll get back to you as soon as I know.

500
00:45:41,900 --> 00:45:45,600
- What's happening, Joe?
- BMEWS and Cobra Dane now report

501
00:45:46,000 --> 00:45:49,100
negative confirmation
on all inbound tracking.

502
00:45:50,300 --> 00:45:53,000
Get onto SAC. Tell 'em to hold steady.

503
00:45:55,000 --> 00:45:58,700
Stop! It's a simulation!
There's an attack simulation running!

504
00:45:59,000 --> 00:46:01,300
What the hell's he yelling about?
I didn't order that.

505
00:46:01,500 --> 00:46:04,300
We're not being attacked!
It's a simulation!

506
00:46:04,600 --> 00:46:06,200
Whoa, now! Hold it!

507
00:46:06,300 --> 00:46:08,400
You're not supposed to be runnin' here.

508
00:46:08,700 --> 00:46:10,600
We don't know how it happened.

509
00:46:10,900 --> 00:46:14,600
Someone outside fed an attack simulation
into the main... It's a simulation!

510
00:46:15,500 --> 00:46:16,400
Conley...

511
00:46:16,600 --> 00:46:18,400
Take us off full alert.

512
00:46:18,600 --> 00:46:23,100
Hold at DEFCON 4 till we find out exactly
what in the hell's happening here!

513
00:46:23,500 --> 00:46:27,700
I didn't tell you to cut the line!
Did I tell you to cut it? You cut the line!

514
00:46:28,000 --> 00:46:30,700
They shut down
before we could complete our trace.

515
00:46:30,900 --> 00:46:33,900
We did locate the area
where the transmission originated.

516
00:46:34,300 --> 00:46:36,200
- Where?
- Seattle, Washington.

517
00:46:36,400 --> 00:46:38,200
Shut it down!

518
00:46:38,500 --> 00:46:40,600
Somebody's playing a game with us.

519
00:46:40,700 --> 00:46:43,100
At a prophylactic recycling centre...

520
00:46:43,500 --> 00:46:44,400
Hi, Dad!

521
00:46:45,200 --> 00:46:46,400
David!

522
00:46:47,200 --> 00:46:49,400
- David, come in here!
- What did I do?

523
00:46:49,600 --> 00:46:51,600
Plenty, mister. Plenty.

524
00:46:53,500 --> 00:46:56,800
You have just passed
all of your classes this semester.

525
00:46:57,100 --> 00:46:59,000
Congratulations, dear!

526
00:46:59,300 --> 00:47:01,200
Show this to your dad.

527
00:47:01,400 --> 00:47:04,600
Honey! David has something to show you.

528
00:47:04,900 --> 00:47:06,800
- What's that?
- Here, Dad.

529
00:47:07,000 --> 00:47:08,800
Uh-oh.

530
00:47:11,200 --> 00:47:13,100
This is good!

531
00:47:13,400 --> 00:47:15,300
I'm so proud of you!

532
00:47:15,600 --> 00:47:17,700
..went on a full-scale nuclearalert,

533
00:47:18,000 --> 00:47:21,000
believing the Soviet Union
had launched a missile attack.

534
00:47:21,200 --> 00:47:24,500
A spokesman places blame
on a computermalfunction,

535
00:47:24,900 --> 00:47:27,800
emphasising that the problem
has been corrected.

536
00:47:28,100 --> 00:47:31,200
For more on the story,
let's go live to Washington DC.

537
00:47:34,100 --> 00:47:36,000
Well, that's your phone.

538
00:47:36,200 --> 00:47:38,200
Yeah.

539
00:47:38,400 --> 00:47:42,400
Seriously, David. Congratulations.
This one'll be a pleasure to sign!

540
00:47:49,000 --> 00:47:50,700
- Hello?
- David?

541
00:47:50,900 --> 00:47:52,600
Are you watching the news?

542
00:47:52,900 --> 00:47:55,300
Jennifer. Yeah, I'm watching.

543
00:47:55,600 --> 00:47:58,100
David, is that us on TV? Did we do that?

544
00:47:58,300 --> 00:48:00,700
It could be. Oh, Jesus, Jennifer!

545
00:48:00,900 --> 00:48:04,900
What am I gonna do? They're gonna
come get me. I'm really screwed!

546
00:48:05,200 --> 00:48:07,200
I'm screwed!

547
00:48:07,400 --> 00:48:11,000
No! Sh! Calm down!
Sh! Calm down, calm down. Listen...

548
00:48:11,400 --> 00:48:14,200
If they were so smart,
they would have found you already.

549
00:48:14,400 --> 00:48:15,300
Yeah.

550
00:48:15,500 --> 00:48:19,700
OK. So all you have to do is throw
the number away and don't call it again.

551
00:48:20,000 --> 00:48:21,200
- That's all.
- Yeah.

552
00:48:21,500 --> 00:48:26,200
- Maybe they didn't trace the call.
- Right! Maybe they didn't trace the call.

553
00:48:26,500 --> 00:48:30,300
I'm sure they didn't trace the call.
All you have to do is act normal.

554
00:48:30,500 --> 00:48:33,300
We'll both act normal
and everything will be fine.

555
00:48:33,600 --> 00:48:34,900
OK?

556
00:48:35,000 --> 00:48:36,900
- OK.
- OK.

557
00:48:38,200 --> 00:48:41,700
God! This is so unbelievable!
Can I call Michelle and tell her?

558
00:48:42,000 --> 00:48:44,000
No, Jennifer! Don't call her!

559
00:48:44,200 --> 00:48:47,900
Sorry. All right. I won't.
I'll talk to you tomorrow, OK?

560
00:48:48,200 --> 00:48:50,500
OK. Good night, Jennifer.

561
00:49:21,200 --> 00:49:23,800
Greetings, ProfessorFalken.

562
00:49:25,300 --> 00:49:26,700
Oh, my God.

563
00:49:34,500 --> 00:49:38,300
Incorrect identification.

564
00:49:38,600 --> 00:49:40,800
I am not Falken.

565
00:49:41,000 --> 00:49:43,900
Falken is dead.

566
00:49:45,900 --> 00:49:48,200
Sorry to hear that, Professor.

567
00:49:48,400 --> 00:49:50,800
Yesterday's game was interrupted.

568
00:49:51,000 --> 00:49:56,700
Although primary goal has not yet
been achieved, solution is near.

569
00:49:57,200 --> 00:50:02,300
Game time elapsed:
31 hours 12 minutes 50 seconds.

570
00:50:02,700 --> 00:50:09,400
Estimated time remaining:
52 hours 17 minutes 10 seconds.

571
00:50:09,900 --> 00:50:14,100
What is the primary goal?

572
00:50:15,400 --> 00:50:19,100
You should know, Professor.
You programmed me.

573
00:50:19,400 --> 00:50:21,400
Oh, come on.

574
00:50:21,900 --> 00:50:25,100
What is the primary goal?

575
00:50:27,800 --> 00:50:29,600
To win the game.

576
00:51:59,000 --> 00:52:01,100
David Lightman, hold it right there. FBl.

577
00:52:01,300 --> 00:52:03,800
- I'll read you your rights.
- Step over to the van.

578
00:52:04,100 --> 00:52:06,700
You have the absolute right
to remain silent.

579
00:52:07,000 --> 00:52:08,900
What did I do?

580
00:52:09,200 --> 00:52:11,500
You have the right
to consult with an attorney

581
00:52:11,800 --> 00:52:14,000
and to have one present
during questioning.

582
00:52:14,200 --> 00:52:17,900
If you cannot afford an attorney,
one will be appointed to you by the court.

583
00:52:18,200 --> 00:52:20,500
- Do you understand these rights?
- Yeah.

584
00:52:20,800 --> 00:52:24,200
Are you willing to talk to me
about the charges against you?

585
00:52:24,400 --> 00:52:26,400
All right. Let's move.

586
00:52:39,000 --> 00:52:41,700
This rather large room
is command centre for NORAD.

587
00:52:42,100 --> 00:52:46,400
No picture taking. The screens in front
of you are connected to our satellites

588
00:52:46,600 --> 00:52:49,700
and missile tracking stations
throughout the country.

589
00:52:50,000 --> 00:52:53,000
This is the commander's desk.
Colonel Conley is in charge.

590
00:52:53,200 --> 00:52:55,900
Would you mind relinquishing
your command, sir?

591
00:52:56,100 --> 00:52:59,800
Miss Dailey, would you come
and sit in this rather important chair?

592
00:53:00,100 --> 00:53:03,500
These buttons are connected
with the Strategic Air Command

593
00:53:03,900 --> 00:53:05,800
and missile launching stations.

594
00:53:06,000 --> 00:53:09,200
Miss Dailey, would you press
this button here? The red one.

595
00:53:09,500 --> 00:53:11,400
- The one in the middle?
- Yes, ma'am.

596
00:53:11,600 --> 00:53:14,000
Oh, my God! It's the wrong one!

597
00:53:14,200 --> 00:53:17,600
It's a joke! You didn't blow up anything.
Look what you did do.

598
00:53:17,900 --> 00:53:20,600
"Distinguished visitors
from Birmingham."

599
00:53:50,700 --> 00:53:53,500
Last week I had the governor
of New Jersey in this chair.

600
00:53:53,800 --> 00:53:57,800
He said, "Colonel Thomas, why are we
at DEFCON 4?" as we are right now.

601
00:53:58,100 --> 00:54:00,000
Why are we at DEFCON 4?

602
00:54:00,300 --> 00:54:03,100
The Soviets saw our bombers scramble
and went on alert.

603
00:54:03,300 --> 00:54:08,000
We told them it was just an exercise, but
we want them to relax their posture first.

604
00:54:08,300 --> 00:54:09,500
Wait. Wait.

605
00:54:09,800 --> 00:54:12,100
- Give me that.
- Oh, Christ. Another tour group.

606
00:54:12,400 --> 00:54:16,300
Just what we need today. Why don't they
go to Disneyland where they belong?

607
00:54:16,600 --> 00:54:20,500
- Well, I think they're going to tomorrow.
- OK. All set? Oh, here.

608
00:54:23,900 --> 00:54:25,800
It was a one-in-a-million shot.

609
00:54:26,100 --> 00:54:28,800
There was an open line
at our division in Sunnyvale.

610
00:54:29,000 --> 00:54:31,000
The phone company screwed up!

611
00:54:31,200 --> 00:54:34,100
- John. John McKittrick, George Wigan.
- How are you?

612
00:54:34,400 --> 00:54:36,800
George is with the FBl.
He brought the kid in.

613
00:54:37,000 --> 00:54:40,100
It looks like we've got
a high-school prank on our hands.

614
00:54:40,400 --> 00:54:42,100
Paul, what happened?

615
00:54:42,300 --> 00:54:46,900
The kid broke into the war game using a
password left by the original programmer.

616
00:54:47,200 --> 00:54:48,700
- A password?
- Yes, sir.

617
00:54:49,000 --> 00:54:50,900
None of my team even knew it was there.

618
00:54:51,000 --> 00:54:53,600
Kid claims
he was looking for a toy company.

619
00:54:54,000 --> 00:54:57,100
That's great!
Anybody in here buy that one?

620
00:54:57,800 --> 00:55:02,000
We can find the password and take it out,
but it might help to beef up security.

621
00:55:02,300 --> 00:55:04,200
Oh. Beef up, huh?

622
00:55:05,000 --> 00:55:06,400
How about screwed up?

623
00:55:06,700 --> 00:55:09,200
We did all that and he broke in again.

624
00:55:09,400 --> 00:55:12,100
Kid says your computer called him.

625
00:55:12,300 --> 00:55:14,800
What the hell is going on, John?

626
00:55:15,000 --> 00:55:18,900
I woke up the president. I told him
we were under attack by the Russians.

627
00:55:19,300 --> 00:55:23,300
You know what an idiot that makes me
look? Not to mention the general.

628
00:55:23,600 --> 00:55:25,700
I think we're being a little naive here.

629
00:55:25,900 --> 00:55:27,800
There is no way a high-school punk

630
00:55:28,100 --> 00:55:30,900
can put a dime in a telephone
and break into our system.

631
00:55:31,200 --> 00:55:33,400
He's got to be working
with somebody else.

632
00:55:33,600 --> 00:55:37,300
He fits the profile perfectly.
He's intelligent, but an underachiever.

633
00:55:37,600 --> 00:55:40,300
Alienated from his parents.
Has few friends.

634
00:55:40,500 --> 00:55:42,900
Classic case
for recruitment by the Soviets.

635
00:55:43,200 --> 00:55:45,700
What does this say
about the state of our country?

636
00:55:46,000 --> 00:55:50,300
I mean, have you gotten any insight
as to why a bright boy like this

637
00:55:50,700 --> 00:55:52,900
would jeopardise the lives of millions?

638
00:55:53,100 --> 00:55:55,200
He says
he does this sort of thing for fun.

639
00:55:55,500 --> 00:55:58,700
Dammit, John, I want some answers,
and I want 'em now!

640
00:56:02,300 --> 00:56:05,800
- Let me talk to this little prick.
- I don't wanna talk. Just do it!

641
00:56:08,100 --> 00:56:09,600
Come on, Paul.

642
00:56:13,400 --> 00:56:15,300
Who do they belong to? Do you know?

643
00:56:15,500 --> 00:56:16,800
What?

644
00:56:17,100 --> 00:56:18,300
Good morning, sir.

645
00:56:18,400 --> 00:56:21,400
- Where's the Lightman kid?
- In the infirmary, sir.

646
00:56:30,500 --> 00:56:34,600
Hello, David. John McKittrick.
I run the computer facility here.

647
00:56:34,900 --> 00:56:37,500
Sergeant, these aren't necessary,
the handcuffs?

648
00:56:37,700 --> 00:56:39,100
No, sir.

649
00:56:40,300 --> 00:56:43,400
Well, David, we called your parents.

650
00:56:43,700 --> 00:56:46,000
We told them everything's fine.

651
00:56:46,200 --> 00:56:48,900
No charges have been filed... yet.

652
00:56:49,200 --> 00:56:53,700
But I think we are gonna need
a little time to sort things out here.

653
00:56:54,400 --> 00:56:55,800
How much time?

654
00:56:56,000 --> 00:56:59,300
Well, that depends on
how willing you are to cooperate.

655
00:56:59,500 --> 00:57:01,500
Oh, of course.

656
00:57:03,100 --> 00:57:07,000
Sergeant, would you tell the OD
I'm gonna take David for a little walk?

657
00:57:07,300 --> 00:57:10,800
Let's go down to my office.
We'll be more comfortable there.

658
00:57:11,100 --> 00:57:13,100
Go ahead.

659
00:57:17,400 --> 00:57:19,600
You used to work with Stephen Falken?

660
00:57:19,600 --> 00:57:21,900
I started as his assistant.
How d'you know?

661
00:57:22,300 --> 00:57:25,300
I read an article you wrote with him
on poker and nuclear war.

662
00:57:25,400 --> 00:57:27,700
Bluffing. Yeah,
that shook a few people up.

663
00:57:28,000 --> 00:57:31,900
- He must have been pretty amazing.
- He's a brilliant man. A little flaky.

664
00:57:32,300 --> 00:57:36,200
He never understood the practical uses
of his... of his work.

665
00:57:36,500 --> 00:57:39,600
This machine over here
runs his game program.

666
00:57:40,200 --> 00:57:41,300
Joshua.

667
00:57:43,700 --> 00:57:45,400
Come here a minute, David.

668
00:57:47,600 --> 00:57:49,500
See that sign up here? Up here?

669
00:57:49,700 --> 00:57:51,200
- Yeah.
- DEFCON.

670
00:57:51,500 --> 00:57:54,700
That indicates
our current defence condition.

671
00:57:55,000 --> 00:57:57,800
It should read DEFCON 5,
which means peace.

672
00:57:58,000 --> 00:58:01,400
It's still on 4 because of
that little stunt you pulled.

673
00:58:01,700 --> 00:58:05,900
Actually, if we hadn't caught it in time,
it might have gone to DEFCON 1 .

674
00:58:06,200 --> 00:58:09,400
- You know what that means, David?
- No. What does that mean?

675
00:58:09,700 --> 00:58:11,200
World War III.

676
00:58:12,600 --> 00:58:13,600
Wow.

677
00:58:13,700 --> 00:58:16,600
You broke into our system
just to play a game, right?

678
00:58:16,900 --> 00:58:19,200
That's right. That's exactly right.

679
00:58:23,500 --> 00:58:26,400
After the news, you must have
realised how serious it was.

680
00:58:26,700 --> 00:58:28,900
- Why'd you do it again?
- I didn't do it again.

681
00:58:29,200 --> 00:58:31,900
- I even threw the number away.
- They found it in the trash.

682
00:58:32,200 --> 00:58:33,400
Joshua called me.

683
00:58:34,400 --> 00:58:35,500
Hey!

684
00:58:35,600 --> 00:58:37,800
Look at that! That's some setup.

685
00:58:38,100 --> 00:58:41,200
- What did you say?
- This is some setup.

686
00:58:41,500 --> 00:58:43,200
No, no. Before that.

687
00:58:43,300 --> 00:58:45,300
Joshua called me.

688
00:58:47,000 --> 00:58:49,200
David, machines don't call people.

689
00:58:50,600 --> 00:58:52,500
Yours did.

690
00:58:56,200 --> 00:58:58,400
Who are you going to Paris with?

691
00:59:00,500 --> 00:59:01,600
Paris? Oh!

692
00:59:01,900 --> 00:59:03,600
No... You don't understand.

693
00:59:03,800 --> 00:59:06,100
You had reservations for two to Paris.

694
00:59:09,400 --> 00:59:11,600
- Who are you working with?
- Nobody!

695
00:59:13,800 --> 00:59:15,700
Why don't I believe you?

696
00:59:19,100 --> 00:59:22,400
I don't think I should say anything else
until I talk to a lawyer.

697
00:59:24,000 --> 00:59:27,100
I think we'd better forget
about the lawyer crap

698
00:59:27,300 --> 00:59:29,800
until I get a few answers
out of you myself.

699
00:59:48,500 --> 00:59:50,400
Are you gonna answer the phone?

700
00:59:54,700 --> 00:59:55,800
Hello.

701
00:59:55,900 --> 00:59:57,100
Yeah.

702
00:59:57,400 --> 00:59:58,300
What?

703
00:59:59,000 --> 01:00:01,000
All right. I'll be right down.

704
01:00:02,200 --> 01:00:04,100
You stay here. Don't move.

705
01:00:16,200 --> 01:00:17,100
What's going on?

706
01:00:17,400 --> 01:00:21,100
There's been a serious penetration
into our WOPR execution order file.

707
01:00:21,300 --> 01:00:23,600
- What the hell's he sayin'?
- In English.

708
01:00:23,900 --> 01:00:27,200
I'll give it to you. Somebody got
into Mr McKittrick's system

709
01:00:27,400 --> 01:00:30,100
and stole the codes
that'll launch our missiles.

710
01:00:30,300 --> 01:00:33,900
There's no cause for alarm.
The system won't accept a launch code

711
01:00:34,300 --> 01:00:37,800
unless we're at DEFCON 1 .
I can change those codes in an hour.

712
01:00:38,000 --> 01:00:39,400
Well, who did this?

713
01:00:39,700 --> 01:00:42,400
I think the kid's working
with somebody on the outside.

714
01:00:42,700 --> 01:00:47,100
I don't know what they're up to, but
I don't want our bombers on the ground.

715
01:00:47,400 --> 01:00:50,500
Take us to DEFCON 3
and get SAC on the line.

716
01:00:50,800 --> 01:00:53,200
- Where are you?
- Sir.

717
01:00:53,500 --> 01:00:57,600
Get me an update on those subs. I wanna
know what those bastards are up to.

718
01:01:25,200 --> 01:01:27,100
Joshua.

719
01:01:28,600 --> 01:01:30,500
Greetings, ProfessorFalken.

720
01:01:33,800 --> 01:01:34,800
Hello.

721
01:01:35,000 --> 01:01:37,700
Are you still playing the game?

722
01:01:39,900 --> 01:01:42,600
Of course. I should reach DEFCON 1

723
01:01:42,800 --> 01:01:46,400
and launch my missiles in 28 hours.

724
01:01:46,700 --> 01:01:51,000
Would you like to see
some projected kill ratios?

725
01:01:51,300 --> 01:01:53,700
69% of the housing destroyed.

726
01:01:54,600 --> 01:01:57,000
72 million people dead?

727
01:02:01,000 --> 01:02:03,700
Is this a game

728
01:02:04,000 --> 01:02:06,100
or is it real?

729
